  "text": "Mechanisms underlying spatial attention and cognition have a special connection with the right 46 cerebral cortex. Areas in right ventral parieto-temporal and frontal cortex activate in tasks that 47 require attention to detect objects in a stimulus-driven manner or to reorient to new locations 48 [CITATION_1] Shulman et al., 2010) . Mental operations underlying visuo-spatial 49 judgments rely on structures in the right middle frontal gyrus and intraparietal sulcus (Sack et al., 50 2005; [CITATION_2] . Regions in the right intraparietal sulcus also store working memory 51 content for both visual fields for higher loads [CITATION_3] , and magnetic pulses over 52 right frontal eye fields disrupt transsaccadic memory [CITATION_4] . In addition, non-spatial 53 forms of sustained attention activate right ventral regions more so than left ventral regions (e.g., 54",
